04032nam a22006255i 9780271056852DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710568527 a10.1515/97802710568522doi  a(DE-B1597)583971  a(OCoLC)1253313538  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a1922221 aMiller, Ted H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMortal Gods :bScience, Politics, and the Humanist Ambitions of Thomas Hobbes /cTed H. Miller. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b4 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction -- t2 The Humanist Face of Hobbes's Mathematics, Part 1 -- t3 Constraints That Enable the Imitation of God -- t4 King of the Children of Pride: The Imitation of God in Context -- t5 Architectonic Ambitions: Mathematics and the Demotion of Physics -- t6 Eloquence and the Audience Thesis -- t7 All Other Doctrines Exploded: Hobbes, History, and the Struggle over Teaching -- t8 The Humanist Face of Hobbes's Mathematics, Part 2: Leviathan and the Making of a Masque-Text -- t9 Conclusion -- tAppendix: Who Is a Geometer? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAccording to the commonly accepted view, Thomas Hobbes began his intellectual career as a humanist, but his discovery, in midlife, of the wonders of geometry initiated a critical transition from humanism to the scientific study of politics. In Mortal Gods, Ted Miller radically revises this view, arguing that Hobbes never ceased to be a humanist. While previous scholars have made the case for Hobbes as humanist by looking to his use of rhetoric, Miller rejects the humanism/mathematics dichotomy altogether and shows us the humanist face of Hobbes's affinity for mathematical learning and practice. He thus reconnects Hobbes with the humanists who admired and cultivated mathematical learning-and with the material fruits of Great Britain's mathematical practitioners. The result is a fundamental recasting of Hobbes's project, a recontextualization of his thought within early modern humanist pedagogy and the court culture of the Stuart regimes. Mortal Gods stands as a new challenge to contemporary political theory and its settled narratives concerning politics, rationality, and violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271056852?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271056852423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271056852/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK